Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: UACN Property Development, Safaricom Are Active

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-17T15:57:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-17/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-uacn-property-development-safaricom-are-active.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index rose for the fourth day, climbing 0.7 percent to 1,176.24
as of the 3 p.m. end of trading in Accra, the highest since at
least Jan. 4.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index fell for the
first day in six, declined less than 0.1 percent to 25,821.85 by
the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to the exchange’s
website. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index snapped two days of gains,
falling 0.1 percent to 2,110.57 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port
Louis . Kenya’s All-Share Index advanced 0.3 percent to 75.93 by
the 3 p.m. end of trading in Nairobi, the highest closing price
since May 10.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  fell 0.8
percent to 847.64 at the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Safaricom Ltd. (SAFCOM)  , East Africa’s biggest mobile
phone company, fell 5 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 3.95 shillings,
snapping two days of gains, after Business Daily reported a  task
force  appointed by Kenyan Prime Minister  Raila Odinga  backed a
cut in cross-network charges.  UACN Property Development Co. (UACPROP NL), a real estate
developer, rose for the first day in four, gaining 60 kobo, or
3.7 percent, to 17 naira. The company will pay a dividend of 55
kobo per share for the 12 months through December, according to
a statement published in the Punch newspaper.  To contact the reporter on this story:
